content.introtext:
&lt;p&gt;&lt;img style=&quot;margin: 10px; float: right;&quot; alt=&quot;port-hedland&quot; src=&quot;http://www.vision.org.au/images/banners/port-hedland.jpg&quot; height=&quot;267&quot; width=&quot;400&quot; /&gt;A very warm welcome to new listeners just tuning in from the Pilbara region of Western Australia. Vision Port Hedland 87.6 FM went on-air 5th June 2014, right in the town. It complements the service in South Hedland, also transmitting on 87.6 FM.&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;Port Hedland is a dynamic town of over 20,000 people located in the Pilbara region of Western Australia. The original inhabitants, the Karriyarra people, call the place Marapikurrinya for the hand shaped formation of the tidal creeks coming off the natural harbour. It is a port for the huge iron ore and other mineral resources coming out of the Pilbara area, particularly from BHP Billiton mines.&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;The ocean foreshore provides for a variety of aquatic leisure activities. Whales and nesting flatback turtles can be seen in season. Millstream and Karijini National Parks are in easy driving distance, while Broome and the Kimberley are also within reach.&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;It's exciting to see a new Vision station come on air in this location because there were no appropriate frequencies available in this area. Thanks to the efforts of members of the Hedland Christian Church, BHP Billiton gifted the licence they owned to the fellowship!&amp;nbsp; It is our 591st installation nationwide and the 132nd in WA.&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;The countdown is on! Just 9 to go until the huge milestone of 600 stations!&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;&lt;a target=&quot;_self&quot; title=&quot;Vision Programme Guides&quot; href=&quot;http://www.vision.org.au/vision/programme-guides&quot;&gt;A programme guide for Port Hedland (and the other 131 stations in Western Australia) can be found here.&lt;/a&gt;&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;&lt;img style=&quot;margin: 10px; float: right;&quot; alt=&quot;warburton2&quot; src=&quot;http://www.vision.org.au/images/warburton2.jpg&quot; height=&quot;214&quot; width=&quot;320&quot; /&gt;A very warm welcome to listeners just tuning in from the Warburton Ranges Mirlirrtjarra Community of the Gibson Desert in Western Australia. Also to new listeners from the Surat Basin of Queensland, especially in the Condamine North area.&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;Warburton is a tiny indigenous settlement of the Warburton Ranges Mirlirrtjarra Community. About 400 people live in the settlement. Over 1000 km from Alice Springs (where their postal address is) and more than 900 km by the better road from Kalgoorlie in WA, Warburton is located between the Gibson Desert and the Great Victoria Desert. Here the aboriginal people still go hunting and gathering their bush tucker in traditional ways. There are also many artists here, specialising in painting, artefacts and artglass.&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;Warburton was the first Community to be established as a result of the activities of the United Aboriginal Missionaries (UAM). Will and Iris Wade established a base here in the 1930s.&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;Prior to the establishment of the Warburton Mission, the Yarnangu people led a nomadic subsistence life. A prolonged drought drew people into the mission. In the early days of the mission, rations were given to them in exchange for dingo scalps that the missionaries traded for money on their regular trips into Laverton. This trade was lucrative enough to allow the missionaries to establish a school, a dormitory system, a church, a hospital and several cottage industries.&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;Vision Warburton 88.0FM is the 589th installation nationwide and the 131st in Western Australia. It was installed on 9 May 2014.&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;The second station in the last fortnight has been Condamine North, established near the new mining camps in the Surat Basin. Because the mines near Miles are privately-owned, it is not possible for chaplains or ministers to go onto the bases to help with the spiritual needs of the workers. The passion of locals to raise money for radio stations as a way of ministering the Gospel to these fly-in fly-out miners is exceptional.&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;Although only 400 people officially live in the wider Condamine area, there are many more workers benefit by the presence of our latest station, Vision Condamine 87.6 FM.&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;It is of course our 590th installation nationwide. Its also the 190th station in Qld.&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;Only 10 stations to go before we reach the next big milestone: 600 stations.&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;&lt;a target=&quot;_self&quot; title=&quot;Vision Programme Guide&quot; href=&quot;http://www.vision.org.au/vision/programme-guides&quot;&gt;Programme guides for Warburton and Condamine North can be found here.&lt;/a&gt;&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;div class=&quot;iguana iguana-rich-editable&quot;&gt;
&lt;p&gt;&lt;img src=&quot;http://www.vision.org.au/images/images/robbo-dave-aimee.jpg&quot; width=&quot;380&quot; height=&quot;253&quot; alt=&quot;robbo-dave-aimee&quot; style=&quot;float: right;&quot; /&gt;Robbo and Dave Beard will be in &lt;strong&gt;Dalby&lt;/strong&gt; &amp;amp; &lt;strong&gt;Kingaroy &lt;/strong&gt;Monday 3rd &amp;amp; Tuesday 4th February. They would really love the opportunity to meet up with you and other UCB supporters to say &quot;hello&quot; while they're in town.&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;Please come join them at one of the following locations:&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;&lt;em&gt;DALBY&lt;/em&gt; &lt;br /&gt; &lt;strong&gt;Monday 3rd February &lt;/strong&gt;&lt;br /&gt;&lt;strong&gt; Dalby Presbyterian Church&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;br /&gt;&lt;em&gt; Cnr Condamine &amp;amp; Patrick Streets&lt;/em&gt;&lt;/p&gt;
