&lt;p&gt;A very warm welcome to listeners tuning in from three diverse localities across Australia: Wundowie, birthplace of WA's iron ore industry and home of the Iron Beast competition; Tamworth, birthplace of street lights in Australia - though of course better known as our Country Music capital; and Healesville in Victoria's Yarra Valley, remembered by many Aussies because of the Black Saturday bushfires of 2009.&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;Vision Wundowie 87.6FM began broadcasting on Thursday 23 May - our 120th station in WA.&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;Vision Tamworth 1611AM and Vision Healesville 87.6FM both started transmissions on Saturday 25 May. Tamworth is our 78th station in NSW and Healesville our 49th in Victoria.&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;&lt;a href=&quot;http://vision.org.au/vision/programme-guides&quot; target=&quot;_self&quot;&gt;Programme guides for these new stations can be found here.&lt;/a&gt;&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;&amp;nbsp;&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;A massive welcome to four very diverse communities across Australia, all joining the Vision family last week. The smallest is Mulan (pronounced 'mullen', not like the Disney film!) in WA which arrived officially on Wednesday October 3. This tiny town at the top of the Tanami Desert is one of the most expensive places to live in Australia.&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;Two NSW towns around the same size joining us are Marrangaroo on the Central Tablelands and Tingha on the Central Tablelands. And finally Red Cliffs near Mildura came on air on Saturday October 6.&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;Programme guides for Vision Marrangaroo 87.8 FM, Vision Mulan 88.0 FM, Vision Tingha 88.0 FM and Vision Red Cliffs 87.6 FM are &lt;a target=&quot;_self&quot; href=&quot;http://www.vision.org.au/vision/programme-guides&quot; title=&quot;Vision Programme Guides&quot;&gt;available here&lt;/a&gt;.&lt;/p&gt;

