&lt;p&gt;The Federal election is upon us and the various parties are trying hard to win our vote. Have you decided who you'll vote for?... Do you even know who is running in your electorate?&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;Thankfully, it's not hard to cut through all the rhetoric and find out who the candidates are and where stand on matters of Christian values.&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;Below are links to the results of several questionnaires that show where the parties, our leaders, and even the individual candidates running for your local electorate stand on matters of Christian values, the economy, health, education and more.&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;So if having Christian values in government is important to you, &lt;span style=&quot;text-decoration: underline;&quot;&gt;before you vote&lt;/span&gt;, take a few minutes to learn who best represents those values. It's a sure way of knowing your vote will really count.&lt;/p&gt;

content.fulltext:
&lt;h2&gt;Helpful Links&lt;/h2&gt;
&lt;h3&gt;Australia Votes (Australian Christian Lobby)&lt;/h3&gt;
&lt;p&gt;The Australian Christian Lobby put 24 questions to each of the political parties on key issues of concern to Christians. Their aim was to highlight the parties' positions on issues of significant interest to Christians, which will not necessarily be prominently discussed in the wider election coverage.&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;ACL recognises that Christian voters will share many concerns with the general electorate and has tried to avoid duplicating those. Instead their questionnaire aims to reflect the main concerns of Christians on topics such as refugees, abortion, climate change, marriage, family, indigenous well-being, classification standards, sexualisation of children, religious freedom and chaplaincy.&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Visit &lt;a href=&quot;http://www.australiavotes.org.au&quot; target=&quot;new&quot;&gt;www.australiavotes.org.au&lt;/a&gt;.&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;h3&gt;Family Voice Australia&lt;/h3&gt;
&lt;p&gt;Before each election FamilyVoice Australia (formerly Festival of Light Australia) sends candidates a &lt;a href=&quot;http://www.fava.org.au/media/docs/2010_fed_election_fava_questionnaire.pdf&quot; target=&quot;new&quot;&gt;questionnaire&lt;/a&gt; with ten statements on family-related issues.  Candidates are invited to express their agreement or otherwise with each statement on the scale: &lt;em&gt;Yes definitely, Probably, Unsure, Unlikely, Definitely not, or No comment.&lt;/em&gt;&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;Each response is scored out of 10 so the maximum total score is 100.  Our scoring system is designed to encourage honest replies.  Those who decline to answer a question score zero for that question - but &quot;Definitely not&quot; scores two, with more for other answers, while those who answer &quot;No comment&quot; will score one.&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;Family Voice Australia sent their &lt;a href=&quot;http://www.fava.org.au/media/docs/2010_fed_election_fava_questionnaire.pdf&quot; target=&quot;new&quot;&gt;questionnaire&lt;/a&gt; to every candidate and their website lists responses from them all.&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;&lt;strong&gt;View responses from: &lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;li&gt;&lt;strong&gt;&lt;a href=&quot;http://polls.fol.org.au/survey/e/25/q/41/view&quot; target=&quot;new&quot;&gt;Senate Candidates listed by state&lt;/a&gt;. &lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;li&gt;&lt;strong&gt;&lt;a href=&quot;http://polls.fol.org.au/survey/e/23/q/41/view&quot; target=&quot;new&quot;&gt;Lower House Candidates listed by state and electorate&lt;/a&gt;.&lt;/strong&gt;
&lt;h3&gt;Saltshakers&lt;/h3&gt;
&lt;p&gt;SALT SHAKERS is a Christian Ethics Action Group based in Melbourne. Their website has many insightful articles regarding the election and many other issues.&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Visit &lt;a href=&quot;http://www.saltshakers.org.au&quot; target=&quot;new&quot;&gt;www.saltshakers.org.au&lt;/a&gt;.&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;h3&gt;Australian Electoral Commission&lt;/h3&gt;
&lt;p&gt;If you're unsure of which electorate you're in, the AEC website can tell you. It also has lots of use information on who your local candidates are, where and how to vote - you can even fill out a practice ballot so you know exectly what to do come polling day.&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Visit &lt;a href=&quot;http://www.aec.gov.au/&quot; target=&quot;new&quot;&gt;www.aec.gov.au&lt;/a&gt;.&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/p&gt;
